    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>First of all, I want to say that <code>@s1m0nw1</code>'s answer is awesome. Kotlin's <code>spread operator</code> (or <code>*</code>) lets you decompose an array into a list of individual elements when passing it to a function. However, I'd like to show you how to convert Kotlin's <code>Array</code> to Java's <code>Varargs</code> without spread operator. Here's the code:</p>\n<pre><code>fun toListFrom(vararg severalStrs: String): List&lt;String&gt; {\n    return severalStrs.asList()\n}\n\nfun main() {\n    val elements = arrayOf(&quot;He&quot;,&quot;l&quot;,&quot;lo&quot;,&quot; &quot;,&quot;Kot&quot;,&quot;li&quot;,&quot;n!&quot;)\n    val concatenation = toListFrom(elements.reduce { a, b -&gt; a + b })\n    val result = concatenation.first()\n\n    println(result)                          // Hello Kotlin!\n}\n</code></pre>\n<hr />\n<p>And this is what my code will look like if I use <code>*</code> spread operator.</p>\n<pre><code>fun concatenate(vararg severalStrs: String): String {\n    return severalStrs.reduce { a, b -&gt; a + b }\n}\n\nfun main() {\n    val elements = arrayOf(&quot;He&quot;,&quot;l&quot;,&quot;lo&quot;,&quot; &quot;,&quot;Kot&quot;,&quot;li&quot;,&quot;n!&quot;)\n    val concat = concatenate(*elements)\n\n    println(concat)                          // Hello Kotlin!\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Tested on Kotlin 2.0.0 Playground.</p>\n"
  } ],
